# nalgebra-glm − nalgebra in _easy mode_
    **nalgebra-glm** is a GLM-like interface for the **nalgebra** general-purpose linear algebra library.
    [GLM](https://glm.g-truc.net) itself is a popular C++ linear algebra library essentially targeting computer graphics. Therefore
    **nalgebra-glm** draws inspiration from GLM to define a nice and easy-to-use API for simple graphics application.

defs.name: abs
defs.value: fn <N, R, C> (x: &TMat<N, R, C>) -> TMat<N, R, C>

defs.name: clamp_scalar
defs.value: fn <N> (x: N, min_val: N, max_val: N) -> N
defs.docs: Returns `min(max(x, min_val), max_val)`.

defs.name: clamp
defs.value: fn <N, D> (x: &TVec<N, D>, min_val: N, max_val: N) -> TVec<N, D>
defs.docs:
Returns `min(max(x[i], min_val), max_val)` for each component in `x`
 using the values `min_val and `max_val` as bounds.

defs.name: clamp_vec
defs.value: fn <N, D> (x: &TVec<N, D>, min_val: &TVec<N, D>, max_val: &TVec<N, D>) -> TVec<N, D>
defs.docs:
Returns `min(max(x[i], min_val[i]), max_val[i])` for each component in `x`
 using the components of `min_val` and `max_val` as bounds.

defs.name: int_bits_to_float_vec

defs.name: mix
defs.value: fn <N> (x: N, y: N, a: N) -> N
defs.docs: Returns `x * (1.0 - a) + y * a`, i.e., the linear blend of x and y using the floating-point value a.

defs.name: sign

defs.name: smoothstep
defs.value: fn <N> (edge0: N, edge1: N, x: N) -> N
defs.docs: Returns 0.0 if `x <= edge0` and `1.0 if x >= edge1` and performs smooth Hermite interpolation between 0 and 1 when `edge0 < x < edge1`.

defs.name: step_scalar
defs.docs: Returns 0.0 if `x < edge`, otherwise it returns 1.0.

defs.name: step

defs.name: step_vec
defs.value: fn <N, D> (edge: &TVec<N, D>, x: &TVec<N, D>) -> TVec<N, D>
defs.docs: Returns 0.0 if `x[i] < edge[i]`, otherwise it returns 1.0.

defs.name: trunc

defs.name: faceforward
defs.value: fn <N, D> (n: &TVec<N, D>, i: &TVec<N, D>, nref: &TVec<N, D>) -> TVec<N, D>

defs.name: length
defs.docs: The magnitude of a vector.

defs.name: magnitude

defs.name: normalize

defs.name: reflect_vec
defs.value: fn <N, D> (i: &TVec<N, D>, n: &TVec<N, D>) -> TVec<N, D>
defs.docs: For the incident vector `i` and surface orientation `n`, returns the reflection direction : `result = i - 2.0 * dot(n, i) * n`.

defs.name: refract_vec
defs.value: fn <N, D> (i: &TVec<N, D>, n: &TVec<N, D>, eta: N) -> TVec<N, D>
defs.docs: For the incident vector `i` and surface normal `n`, and the ratio of indices of refraction `eta`, return the refraction vector.
